{"parentUuid":"0b168e86-8e11-4c79-9b4b-f5adc099956a","isSidechain":true,"userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/nicholasfeyintolafolarin-coker/trellomcp/trello-mcp/projects","sessionId":"5fd7138a-bf9d-4e52-8925-ae39a47b756c","version":"2.1.39","gitBranch":"master","agentId":"aee1469","slug":"lexical-snuggling-thimble","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01YHq1H5higvQfH1v65y3YUR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01XrVEeXJ8zB7hhqinjBPPfR","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/Users/nicholasfeyintolafolarin-coker/trellomcp/trello-mcp/projects/learn/video-kb/bookmarks/2026-02-11-jack-butcher-sawdust/index.md","content":"---\ntitle: \"Jack Butcher — Selling Your Sawdust / Proof of Work\"\nsource: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wZc5yoYRKuY\ndate_processed: 2026-02-11\nspeaker: Jack Butcher (Visualize Value)\nduration: ~39 minutes\nformat: Office Hours / Live Presentation with Q&A\ntags: [proof-of-work, selling-sawdust, flywheel, content-strategy, audience-building, trust, service-business, marketing]\nrelevance: [aloe-labs, content-marketing, growth-strategy]\n---\n\n# Jack Butcher: Selling Your Sawdust & Proof of Work\n\n## Source Video\n- **URL:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wZc5yoYRKuY\n- **Speaker:** Jack Butcher, founder of Visualize Value\n- **Context:** Office hours session answering community questions about entrepreneurship, audience building, and marketing for service/mentorship products\n\n---\n\n## THE CORE THESIS\n\n**\"Nobody cares what you can do. Everybody cares what you can do for them.\"**\n\nThis is the foundational lesson. Jack credits Matthew Kobach (social media at NYSE) who spent years on a PhD studying social media behavior and concluded in one sentence: \"People treat social media interactions the same way they treat real-life interactions. Helpful people are valued, whereas self-serving people are ignored.\"\n\nSimple concept. Hard to stick to in practice.\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 1: THE WRONG QUESTION (Audience-First Fallacy)\n\n### The Common Approach (Wrong)\n```\nSmall Audience ──────────> Big Audience ──────> Drop Product On Them\n```\n\nThe typical approach: grow audience first using tactics (100 different people can teach you how), then introduce a product later. Problem: the overlap between your audience and your product-market is **minimized**.\n\n**Why it fails:** You build reach without relevance. The audience you attract through generic growth tactics may have zero alignment with the product you eventually sell.\n\n### The Right Question\nInstead of \"How do I grow my audience?\" ask \"How do I develop my product AND audience simultaneously so they're perfectly aligned?\"\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 2: CREATIVITY AS COLLABORATION\n\n**Key Quote (Marc Andreessen):** \"Creativity is a collaborative exercise between the creator and the audience.\"\n\n### The Venn Diagram\n```\n┌─────────────┐     ┌─────────────┐\n│             │     │             │\n│  AUDIENCE   │─────│   PRODUCT   │\n│  (mentees,  │COLLA│ (mentorship,│\n│   clients)  │BORA-│  service,   │\n│             │TION │  course)    │\n└─────────────┘     └─────────────┘\n```\n\n**What the overlap means:**\n- LEFT SIDE: What people aspire to learn (where your audience is in their journey)\n- RIGHT SIDE: What you're an expert at\n- MIDDLE: Where the value lies — the collaboration, the exchange\n\n**The problem:** Most content creation is ONE-WAY traffic. People produce content and push a message without taking into account where the audience is or how they can contribute to make content more relevant.\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 3: SELLING YOUR SAWDUST\n\nThis is the central metaphor. When a woodworker makes furniture (the product), they produce sawdust as a byproduct. That sawdust has value.\n\n### The Sawdust Metaphor Applied\n```\nYOUR WORK (building products, serving clients)\n    │\n    ├── THE PRODUCT (furniture) ── what you sell\n    │\n    └── THE SAWDUST (shavings) ── content, lessons, mistakes,\n                                    process, insights\n                                    ── what draws people TO\n                                       the product\n```\n\n**Key insight:** The process of getting to a point where you CAN sell a product involves:\n- Making a ton of mistakes\n- Shaving off things that don't work\n- Shaving off things that DO work\n- Honing and refining\n\nALL OF THAT is content. In real time. You don't need to manufacture content separately.\n\n### How It Works\n```\nDeveloping Product ──> Sharing Process ──> Building Relationships\n       │                      │                      │\n       │                      │                      │\n       ▼                      ▼                      ▼\n  Product takes          Content as           Audience grows\n  shape itself          byproduct of          with perfect\n                        real work              alignment\n```\n\n**Instead of:**\n1. Build product in silence\n2. Build audience separately\n3. Try to match them together (low overlap)\n\n**Do this:**\n1. Develop the product\n2. Help people in real time AS you develop\n3. Find out what people need while producing content that PROVES you understand their needs\n4. Product takes shape through this process\n5. Build relationships and give value as a byproduct of product development\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 4: PROOF OF WORK\n\n**\"Proof of Work\" is the most overlooked but easiest marketing device to figure out.**\n\n### What Proof of Work Means\nIn the service industry especially, people just want to know you're CAPABLE of the thing you're selling. Sounds obvious, but the blind spot is:\n\n> \"When we do marketing or talk to an audience, we tend to jump too many stages past what we're actually doing. We don't showcase the work we're doing. We don't figure out ways to use our competency and the things we're working on every day to build that audience.\"\n\n### The Gap\n```\nWhat you're actually doing every day\n         │\n    [HUGE GAP]  <── wasted energy\n         │\nWhat your marketing says\n```\n\n**The fix:** Align the two as closely as possible. The work you produce for paying clients IS your marketing.\n\n### Proof of Work is Simple\n> \"You don't have to over-engineer proof of work. You just help someone do something and then ask them how it was. In that process you get a ton of material to help someone else go through that process.\"\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 5: START WITH AN AUDIENCE OF ONE\n\n### The 1:1 to 1:Many Progression\n```\n1:1                    1:Few                  1:Many\n┌──┐                 ┌────────┐          ┌──────────────┐\n│  │ ──────────>     │        │ ──────>  │              │\n│OO│                 │ O    O │          │   O        O │\n│  │                 │   O    │          │ O   PRODUCT  │\n└──┘                 └────────┘          │     O    O   │\nPROOF OF WORK                            └──────────────┘\n```\n\nInstead of spraying and praying to a huge generic audience:\n\n1. **Start with ONE person** — someone you want to help get from where you were to where you are\n2. **That process produces** interactions, content, questions, jump-off points\n3. **Use that material** to create content that resonates with MORE people in that situation\n4. **Building from an audience of one** is far more useful than growing a huge audience of people \"generally interested in entrepreneurship or marketing\"\n\n### The First Person Can Be Free\n> \"If you're doing this for the first time, maybe even do this complementary with someone who really wants to work with you. You both benefit massively from it. You get an enormous amount of social proof, a huge amount of content, and you get to refine the product in real time.\"\n\nAll the energy you would have spent on one-way broadcasted marketing material gets redirected towards actually generating a RESULT for someone and recording that process.\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 6: THE SAWDUST-TO-TRUST-TO-SALES FLYWHEEL\n\n### The Bridge: Trust\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│                   Trust                      │\n│        ┌──────────────────────┐              │\n│        │                      │              │\n│   ┌────┴────┐            ┌────┴────┐        │\n│   │ SAWDUST │            │  SALES  │        │\n│   │         │            │         │        │\n│   │Articles │            │Products │        │\n│   │Emails   │            │Services │        │\n│   │Video    │            │         │        │\n│   │Audio    │            │         │        │\n│   │Images   │            │         │        │\n│   │Case     │            │         │        │\n│   │Studies  │            │         │        │\n│   │Social   │            │         │        │\n│   │Proof    │            │         │        │\n│   │Process  │            │         │        │\n│   └─────────┘            └─────────┘        │\n│                                              │\n│          \"Show me, don't tell me.\"           │\n│                                              │\n│              Proof of Work                   │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n**The gap we're trying to leap = TRUST.** Someone sees how much you give away about your process and thinks: \"If they're giving away THIS much for free, there must be enormous value behind the paywall.\"\n\n### The Loop\n```\nProduce Sawdust ──> Prove Efficacy ──> Convert to Sales ──> More Work\n       ▲                                                        │\n       │                                                        │\n       └────────────── More Sawdust ◄──────────────────────────┘\n```\n\nThe byproduct of the energy you put in increases the flywheel as it works. Each client served = more proof = more content = more clients.\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 7: PIECES AND PARTS\n\n### Left Side: Sawdust (Pieces)\nIndividual content assets — each one addresses ONE concept, ONE page of the \"textbook,\" ONE specific experience with a lesson embedded in it. Posted organically. Gradually builds relationships.\n\n### Right Side: Sales (Parts)\nThe compiled, structured, refined product — course, mentorship, community, etc.\n\n### The Connection\nThe pieces DON'T exist separately from the course. They INFORM the curriculum you're building. You get feedback from the audience in real time, and the product evolves in lockstep with what resonates.\n\n### Progression\n```\nPieces (free content) ──> Low-barrier entry (community) ──> Comprehensive product\n```\n\nStart with something that isn't a hard sell. Community is a great example — simple, low barrier to entry. Use it to get the right people around you. Develop the more comprehensive asset over time, potentially by working 1:1 with someone from the community.\n\n---\n\n## FRAMEWORK 8: COME FOR THIS, STAY FOR THE MEMBERSHIP / BUILD IT ONCE, SELL IT TWICE\n\n**\"Come for [the free content], stay for the membership. Build it once, sell it twice.\"**\n\nYou're exposing what you're doing in real time while moving the product forward. The content and the product development are the SAME activity.\n\n---\n\n## REAL-WORLD EXAMPLES\n\n### 1. Chris Do (@thechrisdo)\n- Been a designer, done the work, been in all the meetings\n- Now compresses those experiences into new assets\n- People trust his course BECAUSE he's gone through that process with X number of clients\n- Refers to real stories in his teaching = authority through proof of work\n- Uses Instagram Q&A as a proof-of-work mechanism\n\n### 2. Jack Butcher / Visualize Value\n**Sawdust (Pieces):**\n- Social media visualizations (complex ideas made simple daily)\n- Blog posts, behind-the-scenes process\n- Whiteboard sessions\n\n**Sales (Parts):**\n- Daily Manifest community (consumer-side paid product)\n- B2B consulting (high-ticket: $10K/month retainer for visual communication)\n\n**How the flywheel works:** Someone running a money management company or mortgage platform sees Jack's ability to visualize complex ideas EVERY DAY. They're getting hit with proof of work consistently. They understand: \"This is what I can expect if I engage this person.\"\n\n### 3. Craig (Community Member — Live Case Study)\n- Runs a digital agency (branding + digital, web apps)\n- Was doing projects in the 5-10K GBP range\n- Changed his sales deck to VISUALIZE their values, process, and promises\n- Changed his Twitter to share values and good content\n- Result: Close to landing a project worth 80-90K GBP (8-10x increase)\n- The lead came FROM Twitter — saw his tweets, already knew him, lived within 20 miles\n- Everything matched up: tweets matched the sales deck matched the delivery\n\n**Key quote from Craig:** \"Previous to doing that we were probably looking at maybe projects within five to ten thousand pounds... and we're really close to landing a project that's around eighty to ninety thousand quid, purely based on changing our slide deck to be more about our values and visualizing and showing our process.\"\n\n**Jack's response:** \"When you start to realize that compounding benefit... the presence in somebody's mind just amplifies because you're talking the same language every time they encounter your name or brand.\"\n\n### 4. In service businesses:\n\n**Before (competition):** Disorganized, don't look at the whole problem, messy\n**After (you):** Systematic, organized, linear\n\n### Example: Supply Chain Company\n```\nTHE OLD WAY                    THE NEW WAY\n┌─────────────────┐           ┌─────────────────┐\n│ Siloed           │           │ Full-Stack       │\n│ Specialists      │           │ Partners         │\n│                  │           │                  │\n│ Consultant A     │           │ Unified vision   │\n│ Consultant B     │           │ Top-down clarity │\n│ Vendor C         │           │ Bottom-up        │\n│ Vendor D         │           │ optimization     │\n│                  │           │                  │\n│ Inefficient      │           │ Efficient        │\n│ Slow             │           │ Rapid            │\n│ Expensive        │           │ Cost Effective   │\n└─────────────────┘           └─────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Your Vulnerability Slide\n```\nINTELLECTUAL POWER ──(described verbally)──> RESULT\n     ●●●                                      ● ●\n     ●●●              ──────>                ●   ●\n     ●●●                                   ●  ●  ●\n     ●●●                                     ●\n\n  (organized)        (lossy translation)    (scattered)\n```\n\nThe sell for Visualize Value: Your ability to deliver a result is your most valuable asset. Your vulnerability is that you're not able to tell that story in a compelling way. Everybody cares what you can do for them.** The foundational truth.\n\n2. **Helpful people are valued. Self-serving people are ignored.** Online and offline, same rules apply.\n\n3. **Don't build audience and product separately.** The overlap will be minimal. Build them together.\n\n4. **Creativity is collaborative.** What's happening between you and your audience drives product development AND audience quality simultaneously.\n\n5. **Sell your sawdust.** The byproduct of doing your actual work IS your content. Don't manufacture content separately.\n\n6. **Content is a byproduct, not a separate activity.** As you develop your product and hone your skills, you produce content naturally.\n\n7. **Proof of work is the most overlooked and easiest marketing device.** Help someone, ask how it went, use that as content.\n\n8. **Start with an audience of one.** Take one person through the transformation. Record that process. That's more valuable than spraying to thousands.\n\n9. **The first one can be free.** The social proof, content, and product refinement you get from a free engagement is worth more than the revenue.\n\n10. **The gap we're leaping is TRUST.** Sawdust builds trust. Trust converts to sales. Sales produce more sawdust.\n\n11. **Show me, don't tell me.** Proof of work over polished marketing copy.\n\n12. **Build it once, sell it twice.** The process of developing the product IS the marketing for the product.\n\n13. **Pieces inform the whole.** Individual content pieces should inform the curriculum/product you're building, not exist separately.\n\n14. **Consistency compounds.** One format, produced consistently, creates the flywheel effect. Don't commit to a format you can't sustain.\n\n15. **Align what you do daily with what your marketing says.** Close the gap between actual work and marketing messaging.\n\n16. **Visualize transformations.** Before/after is universal. The Wrong Question (Audience-First Fallacy)\nGrowing audience first, then dropping product on them = minimal overlap. Build both simultaneously instead.\n\n### 2. Creativity as Collaboration\nProduct development and audience building should be a Venn diagram with overlap (collaboration), not two separate activities. Marc Andreessen quote: \"Creativity is a collaborative exercise between the creator and the audience.\"\n\n### 3. Selling Your Sawdust\nThe byproduct of doing your actual work IS your content engine. Don't manufacture content separately from building your product/serving clients. The mistakes, the process, the shavings -- that's all sawdust, and sawdust has value.\n\n### 4. Proof of Work\nThe most overlooked and easiest marketing device. People in service businesses just want to know you're CAPABLE. The blind spot: most people's marketing jumps too far past what they're actually doing every day. Fix: show the actual work.\n\n### 5. Start with an Audience of One\nTake ONE person through the full transformation. That process generates more usable content and social proof than spraying to thousands. The first one can even be free -- the proof you get back is worth more.\n\n### 6. The Sawdust-to-Trust-to-Sales Flywheel\nSawdust (articles, emails, video, audio, images, case studies, social proof, process) --builds--> Trust --converts--> Sales (products, services). The loop feeds itself: more sales = more work = more sawdust. Central quote: \"Show me, don't tell me.\"\n\n### 7. Pieces and Parts\nIndividual content pieces (sawdust) are not separate from the product -- they INFORM the curriculum/product you're building. Feedback from the audience shapes the product in real time.\n\n### 8. Come for This, Stay for the Membership / Build It Once, Sell It Twice\nThe process of developing the product IS the marketing.
